(898, 4, '2017-01-09 08:05:01', '2017-01-09 13:05:01', '<span style=\"color: #604678;\"><strong>S for Scripture: Mark 6:50-51</strong></span>\r\n\r\n<sup>50</sup> Immediately he spoke to them and said, ‚ÄúTake courage! It is I. Don‚Äôt be afraid.‚Äù <sup>51</sup> Then he climbed into the boat with them, and the wind died down. They were completely amazed,\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #604678;\"><strong>O for Observation:</strong></span>\r\n\r\nJesus‚Äô disciples are in the middle of the lake. They are straining against the oars and the wind is relentless. The gospel of John says that they had been rowing 3-4 miles against the tempestuous winds. In Eugene Peterson‚Äôs paraphrase of Mark 6 in The Message, he says that it was around four in the morning. Jesus, after spending all night praying, sees his disciples straining against the wind in the middle of the lake. Jesus walks out upon the water towards them, and it says that as he is about to pass them, they see him and become even more terrified, because they think he‚Äôs a ghost. In direct response to the disciples shriek of terror, it says ‚ÄòImmediately‚Äô He spoke these words verse 50 to them: ‚ÄòTake Courage! It is I. Don‚Äôt be afraid.‚Äô In the midst of chaos, Jesus challenges his disciples to seemingly do the impossible and ‚Äòtake courage,‚Äô because He is present, and in His presence, the only one to fear is Him. Jesus was able to walk in complete control in the storm, and then steps into the chaos of the disciples, and brings peace. Amazement was the only proper response of the disciples.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #604678;\"><strong>A for Application:</strong></span>\r\n\r\nWhatever the storm. Whatever the chaos. Whenever we are panicked. Whatever the pain or loss. Whatever the worry. Whenever our circumstances feel like straining against tempestuous winds at four in the morning. When we are at the brink of exhaustion . . . Jesus walks effortlessly. He is not shaken by our circumstances. He isn‚Äôt even provoked to run. Jesus walks.\r\n\r\nAnd in my moments of weakness, often I don‚Äôt need a sermon or a lecture. I need the loaded simplicity of the following three short sentences:\r\n\r\n‚ÄúTake courage! It is I. Don‚Äôt be afraid.‚Äù\r\n\r\nIn my chaos, I can take courage, because I can rest in the courage of Christ. Whenever I feel alone, Jesus is screaming, ‚ÄòIT IS I.‚Äô There is a point in every trial where I feel like quitting, but if the fear is removed and replaced with courage, victory in Jesus is right around the corner.\r\n\r\nSimply put, I fear the wrong things. The waves and the wind may rage, but my Jesus walks on the water and at His words they cease. Whom should be feared but the Lord Jesus. Proper placed fear will result in a life that is defined by being ‚Äòmore than a conqueror.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #604678;\"><strong>P for Prayer:</strong></span>\r\n\r\nFather, thank you that I am never alone in my struggle. May I hear your voice more clearly than I hear the wind and the waves. Fill me with your courage. In you, I cannot be shaken. Amen.', 'S.O.A.P. | Mark 6', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 's-o-a-p-mark-6', '', '', '2017-01-09 08:19:54', '2017-01-09 13:19:54', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8000/?p=898', 0, 'post', '', 0),
