(1060, 4, '2017-03-19 05:00:38', '2017-03-19 10:00:38', '<p class=\"Body\"><em>If you didn\'t get a chance to grab an <strong>Emotional/Spiritual Health Inventory</strong> <span class=\"aBn\" tabindex=\"0\" data-term=\"goog_1233591464\"><span class=\"aQJ\">on Sunday</span></span>, <a href=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/ehs_assessment013.pdf\">CLICK HERE</a>¬†to download a copy.</em></p>\r\n<p class=\"Body\"><em>As you fill out your inventory, here is a guide for what each number represents:</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><em>1 - Not Very True</em>\r\n<em> 2 - Sometimes True</em>\r\n<em> 3- Mostly True</em>\r\n<em> 4 - Very True</em></p>\r\n<p class=\"Body\">After completing the Emotional/Spiritual Inventory, I felt like I had been punched in the gut. This was likely your experience as well. If you put a \'4\' for every answer to every question, then you are either lying, or you\'re Jesus (and you\'re not). For the rest of us, it exposed areas in our Emotional/Spiritual health that are in need of a tune up.</p>\r\n<p class=\"Body\">Part 1 put a magnifying glass on our \'General\' Spiritual \'Formation and Discipleship.\' Your confidence in your spiritual identity, commitment to spiritual disciplines (worship, scripture, prayer) and the local church, awareness of your spiritual giftedness, generosity and participation in the mission of God were assessed. Obviously, the questions in which you scored low reveal areas of weakness in your personal discipleship to Jesus.</p>\r\n<p class=\"Body\">Part 2 of the Inventory was painfully revealing. Personally, my \'Spiritual\' components of my discipleship were healthier than the \'Emotional\' components. What does this expose about me?</p>\r\n<p class=\"Body\">It exposes that even though I claim to understand my spiritual identity and giftedness, am committed to the local church, and regularly read my bible, worship, and pray, I still am deficient in numerous areas of fruitfulness that should come from my obedience.</p>\r\n<p class=\"Body\">Why is this?</p>\r\n<p class=\"Body\">There is a difference between stated beliefs and embedded beliefs. My stated beliefs form my worldview, but my embedded beliefs form my thoughts and behaviors.</p>\r\n<p class=\"Body\">Some of the things that I believe to be true about God in relation to me apparently don\'t always make the trek from my brain down to my heart.</p>\r\n<p class=\"Body\">For instance, I claim to be secure in my identity as a child of God, but also need the approval of others to feel good about myself. The truth of my identity in Christ hasn\'t taken a deep enough root in my heart.</p>\r\n<p class=\"Body\">If you score \'Emotional Adult or Adolescent\' in Part 1, but score as an \'Emotional Child or Infant\' in Part 2, then something is out of whack. Your acts of discipleship should result in your transformation.</p>\r\n<p class=\"Body\">The reason we don\'t experience the transformation that is revealed in high scores in part 2, may be because we don\'t score high in part 1. With that being said, it is possible to score high in part 1, and low in part 2, because we haven\'t allowed our faith to engage our emotions, and there are areas of our lives in which Jesus isn\'t allowed into.</p>\r\n<p class=\"Body\">Go back and look at the results on your Emotional/Spiritual Health Inventory. Which statements did you score low on. Look up the Biblical references beside them. Understanding your areas of weakness is the beginning towards Emotional and Spiritual health. This journey won\'t be easy or painless, but it will be worth it.</p>\r\n<p class=\"Body\">\"It\'s impossible to be Spiritually mature, while remaining Emotionally immature\" (Peter Scazzero, The Emotionally Healthy Church).</p>', 'Looking Beneath the Surface', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'blog-inventory', '', '', '2017-03-20 09:27:48', '2017-03-20 14:27:48', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8000/?p=1060', 0, 'post', '', 0),
