(1085, 4, '2017-03-26 09:12:12', '2017-03-26 14:12:12', 'If we want to live emotionally healthy lives, we must understand how our past experiences affect our present ability to love Jesus and love others. There are many things in your past that shape us, but your family of origin generally is the most powerful influence over who we are.\r\n\r\nThis week you were given the challenge of filling out a Genogram of your family (If you weren\'t able to attend the service, listen to the sermon <a href=\"http://www.pointchurchsermons.com/\">HERE</a>, and download the Genogram insert <a href=\"http://localhost:8000/genogram-insert/\">HERE</a>). Some of you come from completely broken families, and finding unhealthy patterns will come quickly to mind. There will be some of you that come from wonderful families, but I can promise you that you didn\'t come from a perfect family. There are no perfect people, therefore there are no perfect families.\r\n\r\nTake your time filling out your Genogram. This isn\'t an exercise to be rushed through.\r\n\r\nYour first step is to place yourself on the Genogram. Find \'You\' at the bottom of your example Genogram, and circle it if you\'re a female, or draw a square around it if you\'re a male. Write the names of your parents and grandparents beside the appropriate shape. If you don\'t know who your mother or father, or grandparents were, place a question mark by the appropriate shape.\r\n\r\nIf your parents or grandparents remarried, or lived with someone else for an extended period of time, draw another line in the opposite direction with the appropriate shape. If they had children, draw lines down from their line with the appropriate shape.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/one.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-1094 aligncenter\" src=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/one.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"379\" height=\"216\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you have any siblings, you need place them on the same line as you. If they are older, then draw them in to the left of you, and if they are younger, draw them in to the right of you. Give them a \'circle\' or a \'square\' accordingly. ¬†</span>If you are married, draw a short line down from your shape, a longer line across, and a short line up to the shape of your spouse.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/w.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-1091 aligncenter\" src=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/w.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"348\" height=\"176\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Now, take a look at the legend in the middle at the bottom of your handout. If your grandparents, parents, or you have been divorced, separated, or remarried, mark with the appropriate symbol. ¬†</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Next, take a look at the legend at the bottom left hand corner of your handout. ¬†</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Were there, or are there any \'conflicted\' relationships in your family? Maybe there were two people who always lived in a constant state of conflict or dislike towards one another.¬†</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/3.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1092\" src=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/3.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"407\" height=\"224\" /></a>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Were there, or are there any examples of \'cut-off\' relationships in your family? Maybe two people didn\'t speak with or associate with one another for an extended period of time.</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/4.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1093\" src=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/4.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"406\" height=\"223\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Were there, or are there any examples of relationships that lacked \'emotional\' or \'relational\' connection?</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/5.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1086\" src=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/5.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"407\" height=\"197\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Were there, or are there any examples of relationships that experienced enmeshment? This is when a member of the family pressures others in the family to think, act, and feel certain ways.</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/6.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1087\" src=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/6.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"408\" height=\"244\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Were there, or are there any examples of relationships where abuse was present? This can be sexual, physical or emotional.</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/7.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1088\" src=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/7.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"409\" height=\"183\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Now I want you to think of any other unhealthy sinful patterns or themes in your family. Flip your page over and look at the example of Abraham\'s family. There were patterns of lying, jealousy, favorite children, and cut-off relationships. You can write these in the table at the bottom right of the handout. </span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/8.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1089\" src=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/8.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"406\" height=\"220\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Here are some questions to help you diagnose some of these unhealthy patterns and themes in your family. These questions come out of the book \'The Emotionally Healthy Church\' by Peter Scazzero</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">1) Describe each family member with two or three adjectives.</span>\r\n\r\n2) Describe your parents marriages.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">3) How was conflict handled in your family over two to three generations? </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">4) What were some generational themes (addictions, affairs, losses, abuse, divorce, depression, mental illness, depression, children born out of wedlock, etc).</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">5) How did your family do in talking about feelings?</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">6) How was sexuality talked about or not talked about?</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">7) Were there family secrets?</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">8) What was considered success in your family?</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">9) How was money handled? Spirituality? Holidays? Relationships with extended family?</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">10) How did your family\'s ethnicity shape you?</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The final box at the bottom of the handout is titled \'Earthquake Events.\'</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/9.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1090\" src=\"http://localhost:8000/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/9.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"410\" height=\"201\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">These are events that sent shockwaves through your genogram for generations. Were there traumatic losses in the past or present, such as sudden death, prolonged illnesses, stillbirths/miscarriages, bankruptcy, divorced, etc. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">___________________________________________________________________________</span>\r\n\r\nAgain, take time filling out your Genogram. Don\'t rush this process. Some people take courses that train them how to do this, and it can take some people up to a year or more. This exercise is the beginning a journey for you, as you examine some of the unhealthy and sinful patterns in your life. As time goes on, you will continue to find more and more things beneath the surface of your life that come from unhealthy patterns from your family of origin. ¬†What\'s the point of this exercise? The point isn\'t to cast blame on your family for the decisions you\'ve made in this life. The point isn\'t to give you an excuse. ¬†The purpose is to find the areas of your life that are shaped by lies, and replace them with the truth of God\'s family. Your parents weren\'t perfect, but God your Father is. Our families aren\'t perfect, but followers of Jesus are adopted into His perfect spiritual family.\r\n\r\nHere are few examples of what it looks like to replace the lie of your family of origin with the truth of God\'s family:\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">-There is a pattern of a struggle of self-worth in your family. In God\'s family, He thought you were worth sending His son Jesus to die for.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">-There is a pattern of a struggle of self-image in your family. In God\'s family, He says you were fearfully and wonderfully made. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">-There is a pattern of addiction in your family. In God\'s family, He says that you are more than a conqueror. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">-There is a pattern of gossip in your family. In God\'s family, He says to not let any unwholesome talk come out of your mouth, but only what is good for building others up. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">-There is a pattern of a lack of forgiveness in your family. In God\'s family, your sins have been forgiven, even though you didn\'t deserve it, therefore you always extend forgiveness. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">-There is a pattern of a need to cling to money in your family. In God\'s family, what you possess was given to you by God, and He calls us to trust Him with it, and be generous with it. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">These are just a few examples, and the list could go on and on, but I hope you get the point. I pray that this exercise brings freedom and liberation in your life. You are not defined by what was done before you, or what you have done in your own life. These events shape you, but in Jesus, you are a new creation. Looking at your Genogram is an exercise in pursuing your new life in Christ. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For further help, feel free to watch this video from Peter Scazzero, walking you through filling out your own Genogram. </span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<iframe src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/135289041\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://vimeo.com/135289041\">Genogram Your Family</a> from <a href=\"https://vimeo.com/user29978616\">Emotionally H Spirituality</a> on <a href=\"https://vimeo.com\">Vimeo</a>.', 'The Genogram', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-genogram', '', '', '2017-03-26 09:12:12', '2017-03-26 14:12:12', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8000/?p=1085', 0, 'post', '', 0),
