(1120, 4, '2017-04-03 09:11:41', '2017-04-03 14:11:41', '<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">On Sunday morning we referred to the ‚Äò5 Stages of Grief‚Äô established by psychiatrist Elizabeth Kluber-Ross. She developed these stages through observing how terminally ill people responded to receiving the news of their terminal illness. Since these stages were established in 1969, they have become influential in describing people‚Äôs grief in all areas of loss, not just terminal illness. </span>\r\n\r\nIt‚Äôs important to note that these 5 stages were her observations of what typically occurred. She didn‚Äôt develop these 5 stages to describe what should occur, or what God‚Äôs process for grieving was.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Robert Kellemen outlines a Biblical response to Ross‚Äô first 4 stages of grief in his book </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Soul Physician.</span></i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Denial vs. Candor</strong>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In the stage of </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Denial, </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">God in His grace, can use it for our good to help us get through the initial response to the loss. However, to remain in a place of </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">denial </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">is harmful, because it runs counter to faith in God. Reality is where we find God, and to deny our reality of loss pushes us further from Him, not closer. Kellemen believes that a Biblical response to the stage of </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">denial</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">candor. </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Here is how Kellemen defines </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">candor:</span></i>\r\n\r\n<i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Candor is courageous truth telling about life to myself in which I come face-to-face with the reality of external and internal suffering</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">David shows us what</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> candor </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">looks like in the Psalm that we read from in our message this Sunday.</span>\r\n\r\n<strong>Psalm 42:3-5</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>3 My tears have been my food</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>¬†¬†¬†¬†day and night,</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>while people say to me all day long,</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>¬†¬†¬†¬†‚ÄúWhere is your God?‚Äù</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>4 These things I remember</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>¬†¬†¬†¬†as I pour out my soul:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>how I used to go to the house of God</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>¬†¬†¬†¬†under the protection of the Mighty One</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>with shouts of joy and praise</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>¬†¬†¬†¬†among the festive throng.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>5 Why, my soul, are you downcast?</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>¬†¬†¬†¬†Why so disturbed within me?</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Put your hope in God,</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>¬†¬†¬†¬†for I will yet praise him,</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>¬†¬†¬†¬†my Savior and my God.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">David shows us what it looks like to be honest with oneself about the ways in which his loss is making him feel. </span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Anger vs. Complaint</strong>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Kelleman makes the point that bringing your </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">complaint </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">before God is beneficial, while settling in your </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">anger </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">is counter-productive. ‚ÄúCursing separates. Complaint connects. Complaint draws us toward God; hatred and anger push us away from God.‚Äù (Kellemen)</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Kellemen defines </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">complaint </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">as follows:</span>\r\n\r\n<i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Complaint is vulnerable frankness about life to God in which I express my pain and confusion over how a good God allows evil and suffering</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span>\r\n\r\nIt is true that the apostle Paul tells us to ‚Äúdo all things without arguing and complaining‚Äù (Phil 2:14), but roughly half of David‚Äôs Psalms are of complaint, rather than thanksgiving. What are we to make of this?\r\n\r\nPaul is referring to ‚Äúcomplaining‚Äù to one another, whereas the Psalms of lament are loaded with complaints directed towards God, who can actually reveal truth, and intervene in the midst of the loss. Believe it or not, bringing your complaints before God can actually increase your faith, rather than sabotaging it.\r\n\r\nLook at this example from the 20th chapter of Jeremiah:\r\n\r\n<strong>Jeremiah 20:7</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>You deceived me, Lord, and I was deceived;</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>¬†¬†¬†¬†you overpowered me and prevailed.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>I am ridiculed all day long;</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>¬†¬†¬†¬†everyone mocks me.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As Jeremiah continues his complaint in this chapter, he becomes aware of the fact that he couldn‚Äôt stop speaking what God had instructed him to speak, because it was like a fire caught up in his bones. In verse 11, Jeremiah declares that God is with him like a ‚Äúmighty warrior.‚Äù As we see from this example, bringing our </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">complaint </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">before God leads us to faith, not faithlessness. </span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Bargaining vs. Cry</strong>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Kluber-Ross closely associated the concept of ‚Äòworks‚Äô with what would normally take place in the </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">bargaining </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">stage. She noticed that people in their last season of life, would often </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">bargain </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">with God to bestow grace on them because of their good behavior. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Kellemen doesn‚Äôt think the </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">bargaining </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">stage draws us close to God, but </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">crying </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">out to him does. Here is how he defines it:</span>\r\n\r\n<i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Cry is a faith-based plea for mobilization in which I humbly ask God for help based upon my admission that I can‚Äôt survive without Him</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Solomon nearly gives this exact same definition for ‚Äò</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">crying‚Äô </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">in Psalm 72:12.</span>\r\n\r\n<strong>Psalm 72:12</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>For he will deliver the needy who cry out,</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>¬†¬†¬†¬†the afflicted who have no one to help.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Crying </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">moves past simply being honest with God, to making bold requests of God. </span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Depression vs. Comfort</strong>\r\n\r\n<i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Depression </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">leads to isolation. </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Comfort </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">finds companionship with God in the midst of the loss. </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Depression </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">is embracing a mindset of hopelessness. </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Comfort </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">finds hope in the presence of God, despite the surrounding loss. Kellemen defines </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">comfort </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">in this way:</span>\r\n\r\n<i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Comfort/communion experiences the presence of God in the presence of suffering‚Äîa presence that empowers me to survive scars and plants the seed of hope that I may yet thrive</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span>\r\n\r\n<i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Depression </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">accepts loss and hopelessness as reality. </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Comfort </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">accepts loss and hope as reality. These words of Asaph in Psalm 73 paint us this picture:</span>\r\n\r\n<strong>Psalm 73:26</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>My flesh and my heart may fail,</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>¬†¬†¬†¬†but God is the strength of my heart</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>¬†¬†¬†¬†and my portion forever.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>_______________</b>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Kellemen‚Äôs four stages that I have outlined here are what he refers to as ‚ÄòSustaining in Suffering.‚Äô Click <a href=\"http://www.aacc.net/email/media/Biblical%20Sufferology.doc\" target=\"_blank\">HERE</a> to download a free excerpt from his book </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Soul Physician, </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">that further explains ‚ÄòSustaining in Suffering‚Äô, and also lays out his steps for ‚ÄòHealing in Suffering.‚Äô </span>', 'Embracing Grief and Loss', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'embracing-grief-and-loss', '', '', '2017-04-03 09:11:41', '2017-04-03 14:11:41', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8000/?p=1120', 0, 'post', '', 0),
